[3] Global support for India
[A] Global response
Date: Mon 26 Apr 2021
Source: CIDRAP [abridged, edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2021/04/indias-covid-19-crisis-prompts-global-response


Several countries over the weekend resoundingly answered India's pleas for help with its massive COVID-19 surge --the worst of the pandemic-- including the United States, which announced it will supply a raw material India urgently needs to make its Covishield vaccine.

India had asked the European Union for oxygen and remdesivir, and the European Commission said it has started the steps to send oxygen and medicine, according to Reuters. Separately, Germany said it will send oxygen and medical aid, and the United Kingdom said it would send oxygen concentrators and ventilators, with the 1st shipment to arrive in New Delhi as early as tomorrow.

Saudi Arabia is sending liquid oxygen, tanks, and oxygen cylinders, and help is also coming from Pakistan, the United Arab Emirates, Canada, China, Hong Kong, Australia, and several other countries, according to India Today.

Global health officials had pinned hopes for millions of doses produced by India's Serum Institute to power the COVAX program, a World Health Organization (WHO)-led effort to equitably distribute vaccine supplies. However, when India's outbreak intensified over the past weeks, in a desperate attempt to immunize more of its own population, it delayed global shipments so that the country could manage its own crisis.

[Byline: Lisa Schnirring]

