[B] US assistance
Date: Mon 26 Apr 2021
Source: Bloomberg News [abridged, edited, subscription required]
https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-04-26/biden-to-send-astrazeneca-doses-abroad-and-pledges-to-help-modi


The U.S. announced on [Mon 26 Apr 2021] that it would share its entire supply of AstraZeneca Plc's Covid-19 vaccine with other countries and readied an aid package for India, as President Joe Biden pivots to ramp up U.S. pandemic assistance to the rest of the world.

The decision would make as many as 60 million vaccine doses available for export in coming months, if they clear a federal safety review. The plan represents a shift for Biden, who has hesitated to give vaccine doses and materials to other countries while focusing on ensuring Americans are vaccinated first.

"Given AstraZeneca is not authorized for use in the United States, we do not need to use AstraZeneca in our fight against Covid over the next few months," @PressSec said.

The U.S. had announced on [Sun 25 Apr 2021] that it would send raw materials for vaccines to India and step up funding for the country to manufacture more doses. Ventilators, therapeutics, rapid testing kits and personal protective equipment will be sent as well, the White House said. While vaccine doses were not included, the U.S. is sending a supply of remdesivir, an anti-viral drug used to treat hospitalized Covid-19 patients, a senior administration official said."

[Byline: Jordan Fabian and Josh Wingrove]

